# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batch-vs-streaming
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] In computing, **batch processing** is the running of a software job in an automated and unattended way.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] A user schedules a job to run and then waits for a processing system to run it.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Typically, a job is scheduled to run at a configured time of day or when an event occurs or when computer resources are available.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] The term "batch processing" originates in the traditional classification of methods of production as job production (one-off production), batch production (production of a "batch" of multiple items at once, one stage at a time), and flow production (mass production, all stages in process at once).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Early computers were capable of running only one program at a time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Each user had sole control of the machine for a scheduled period of time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] They would arrive at the computer with program and data, often on punched paper cards and magnetic or paper tape, and would load their program, run and debug it, and carry off their output when done.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] As computers became faster the setup and takedown time became a larger percentage of available computer time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Programs called *monitors*, the forerunners of operating systems, were developed which could process a series, or "batch", of programs, often from magnetic tape prepared offline.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] The monitor would be loaded into the computer and run the first job of the batch.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] At the end of the job it would regain control and load and run the next until the batch was complete.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Often the output of the batch would be written to magnetic tape and printed or punched offline.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Examples of monitors were IBM's *Fortran Monitor System*, SOS (Share Operating System), and finally IBSYS for IBM's 709x systems in 1960.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Third-generation computers capable of multiprogramming began to appear in the 1960s.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Instead of running one batch job at a time, these systems can have multiple batch programs running at the same time in order to keep the system as busy as possible.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] One or more programs might be awaiting input, one actively running on the CPU, and others generating output.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Instead of offline input and output, programs called spoolers read jobs from cards, disk, or remote terminals and place them in a job queue to be run.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] In order to prevent deadlocks the job scheduler needs to know each job's resource requirements—memory, magnetic tapes, mountable disks, etc., so various scripting languages were developed to supply this information in a structured way.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Probably the most well-known is IBM's *Job Control Language* (JCL).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Job schedulers select jobs to run according to a variety of criteria, including priority, memory size, etc.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Remote batch is a procedure for submitting batch jobs from remote terminals, often equipped with a punch card reader and a line printer.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Sometimes asymmetric multiprocessing is used to spool batch input and output for one or more large computers using an attached smaller and less-expensive system, as in the IBM System/360 Attached Support Processor.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] The first general-purpose time-sharing system, Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), was compatible with batch processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] This facilitated transitioning from batch processing to interactive computing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] From the late 1960s onwards, interactive computing such as via text-based computer terminal interfaces (as in Unix shells or read-eval-print loops), and later graphical user interfaces became common.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation, both one-off jobs such as compilation, and processing of multiple items in batches, became retrospectively referred to as *batch processing*, and the term *batch job* (in early use often "batch *of* jobs") became common.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Early use is particularly found at the University of Michigan, around the Michigan Terminal System (MTS).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Although timesharing did exist, its use was not robust enough for corporate data processing; none of this was related to the earlier unit record equipment, which was human-operated.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Non-interactive computation remains widespread in computing, both for general data processing and for system "housekeeping" tasks (using system software).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] A high-level program (executing multiple programs, with some additional "glue" logic) is today most often called a *script*, and written in scripting languages, particularly shell scripts for system tasks; in IBM PC DOS and MS-DOS this is instead known as a batch file.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] That includes UNIX-based computers, Microsoft Windows, macOS (whose foundation is the BSD Unix kernel), and even smartphones.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] A running script, particularly one executed from an interactive login session, is often known as a job, but that term is used very ambiguously.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] "There is no direct counterpart to z/OS batch processing in PC or UNIX systems.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Batch jobs are typically executed at a scheduled time or on an as-needed basis.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Batch applications are still critical in most organizations in large part because many common business processes are amenable to batch processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] While online systems can also function when manual intervention is not desired, they are not typically optimized to perform high-volume, repetitive tasks.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Therefore, even new systems usually contain one or more batch applications for updating information at the end of the day, generating reports, printing documents, and other non-interactive tasks that must complete reliably within certain business deadlines.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Some applications are amenable to flow processing, namely those that only need data from a single input at once (not totals, for instance): start the next step for each input as it completes the previous step.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] In this case flow processing lowers latency for individual inputs, allowing them to be completed without waiting for the entire batch to finish.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] However, many applications require data from all records, notably computations such as totals.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] In this case the entire batch must be completed before one has a usable result: partial results are not usable.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Modern batch applications make use of modern batch frameworks such as Jem The Bee, Spring Batch or implementations of JSR 352 written for Java, and other frameworks for other programming languages, to provide the fault tolerance and scalability required for high-volume processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] In order to ensure high-speed processing, batch applications are often integrated with grid computing solutions to partition a batch job over a large number of processors, although there are significant programming challenges in doing so.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] High volume batch processing places particularly heavy demands on system and application architectures as well.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Architectures that feature strong input/output performance and vertical scalability, including modern mainframe computers, tend to provide better batch performance than alternatives.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Scripting languages became popular as they evolved along with batch processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] A *batch window* is "a period of less-intensive online activity", when the computer system is able to run batch jobs without interference from, or with, interactive online systems.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] A bank's *end-of-day (EOD)* jobs require the concept of *cutover*, where transaction and data are cut off for a particular day's batch activity ("deposits after 3 PM will be processed the next day").
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] As requirements for online systems uptime expanded to support globalization, the Internet, and other business needs, the batch window shrank and increasing emphasis was placed on techniques that would require online data to be available for a maximum amount of time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] The *batch size* refers to the number of work units to be processed within one batch operation.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] The IBM mainframe z/OS operating system or platform has arguably the most highly refined and evolved set of batch processing facilities owing to its origins, long history, and continuing evolution.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Today such systems commonly support hundreds or even thousands of concurrent online and batch tasks within a single operating system image.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] The Unix programs `cron`, `at`, and `batch` (today `batch` is a variant of `at`) allow for complex scheduling of jobs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/batch-processing] Most high-performance computing clusters use batch processing to maximize cluster usage.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data analysis challenges include capturing data, data storage, data analysis, search, sharing, transfer, visualization, querying, updating, information privacy, and data sources.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data was originally associated with three key concepts: *volume*, *variety*, and *velocity*.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The analysis of big data that have only volume, velocity, and variety can pose challenges in sampling.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A fourth concept, *veracity,* which refers to the level of reliability of data, was thus added.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Current usage of the term *big data* tends to refer to the use of predictive analytics, user behavior analytics, or certain other advanced data analytics methods that extract value from big data, and seldom to a particular size of data set.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] "There is little doubt that the quantities of data now available are indeed large, but that's not the most relevant characteristic of this new data ecosystem." Analysis of data sets can find new correlations to "spot business trends, prevent diseases, combat crime and so on".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Scientists, business executives, medical practitioners, advertising and governments alike regularly meet difficulties with large datasets in areas including Internet searches, fintech, healthcare analytics, geographic information systems, urban informatics, and business informatics.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Scientists encounter limitations in e-Science work, including meteorology, genomics, connectomics, complex physics simulations, biology, and environmental research.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The world's technological per-capita capacity to store information has roughly doubled every 40 months since the 1980s; as of 2012, every day 2.5 exabytes (2.17×260 bytes) of data are generated.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Based on an IDC report prediction, the global data volume was predicted to grow exponentially from 4.4 zettabytes to 44 zettabytes between 2013 and 2020.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] By 2025, IDC predicts there will be 163 zettabytes of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] According to IDC, global spending on big data and business analytics (BDA) solutions is estimated to reach $215.7 billion in 2021.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Statista reported that the global big data market is forecasted to grow to $103 billion by 2027.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2011 McKinsey & Company reported, if US healthcare were to use big data creatively and effectively to drive efficiency and quality, the sector could create more than $300 billion in value every year.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In the developed economies of Europe, government administrators could save more than €100 billion ($149 billion) in operational efficiency improvements alone by using big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] And users of services enabled by personal-location data could capture $600 billion in consumer surplus.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] One question for large enterprises is determining who should own big-data initiatives that affect the entire organization.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Relational database management systems and desktop statistical software packages used to visualize data often have difficulty processing and analyzing big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The processing and analysis of big data may require "massively parallel software running on tens, hundreds, or even thousands of servers".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] What qualifies as "big data" varies depending on the capabilities of those analyzing it and their tools.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Furthermore, expanding capabilities make big data a moving target.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] "For some organizations, facing hundreds of gigabytes of data for the first time may trigger a need to reconsider data management options.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The term *big data* has been in use since the 1990s, with some giving credit to John Mashey for popularizing the term.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data usually includes data sets with sizes beyond the ability of commonly used software tools to capture, curate, manage, and process data within a tolerable elapsed time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data philosophy encompasses unstructured, semi-structured and structured data; however, the main focus is on unstructured data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data "size" is a constantly moving target; as of 2012 ranging from a few dozen terabytes to many zettabytes of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data requires a set of techniques and technologies with new forms of integration to reveal insights from datasets that are diverse, complex, and of a massive scale.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Variability is often included as an additional quality of big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In a comparative study of big datasets, Kitchin and McArdle found that none of the commonly considered characteristics of big data appear consistently across all of the analyzed cases.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] For this reason, other studies identified the redefinition of power dynamics in knowledge discovery as the defining trait.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Instead of focusing on the intrinsic characteristics of big data, this alternative perspective pushes forward a relational understanding of the object claiming that what matters is the way in which data is collected, stored, made available and analyzed.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The quantity of generated and stored data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The size of the data determines the value and potential insight, and whether it can be considered big data or not.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The size of big data is usually larger than terabytes and petabytes.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Earlier technologies like RDBMSs were capable to handle structured data efficiently and effectively.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] However, the change in type and nature from structured to semi-structured or unstructured challenged the existing tools and technologies.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data technologies evolved with the prime intention to capture, store, and process the semi-structured and unstructured (variety) data generated with high speed (velocity), and huge in size (volume).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Later, these tools and technologies were explored and used for handling structured data also but preferable for storage.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Eventually, the processing of structured data was still kept as optional, either using big data or traditional RDBMSs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This helps in analyzing data towards effective usage of the hidden insights exposed from the data collected via social media, log files, sensors, etc.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The speed at which the data is generated and processed to meet the demands and challenges that lie in the path of growth and development.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data is often available in real-time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] , big data is produced more continually.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Two kinds of velocity related to big data are the frequency of generation and the frequency of handling, recording, and publishing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The truthfulness or reliability of the data, which refers to the data quality and the data value.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data must not only be large in size, but also must be reliable in order to achieve value in the analysis of it.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] of captured data can vary greatly, affecting an accurate analysis.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The worth in information that can be achieved by the processing and analysis of large datasets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Value also can be measured by an assessment of the other qualities of big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Value may also represent the profitability of information that is retrieved from the analysis of big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Unlike variety, variability captures the notion the fact that formats, structure, or sources of big data change through time and given different circumstances.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Interpretation of data depends on a changing context, and with a different context, the old meanings may become invalid.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data may or may not include all the available data from sources.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Respectively, the proportion of specific data of each element per element collected and if the element and its characteristics are properly indexed or identified.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] If the data collected contains common fields that would enable a conjoining, or meta-analysis, of different data sets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] If new fields in each element of the data collected can be added or changed easily.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] If the size of the big data storage system can expand rapidly.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data repositories have existed in many forms, often built by corporations with a special need.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Commercial vendors historically offered parallel database management systems for big data beginning in the 1990s.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] For many years, WinterCorp published the largest database report.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Teradata Corporation in 1984 marketed the parallel processing DBC 1012 system.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Teradata systems were the first to store and analyze 1 terabyte of data in 1992.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Hard disk drives were 2.5 GB in 1991 so the definition of big data continuously evolves.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Teradata installed the first petabyte class RDBMS based system in 2007.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] As of 2017, there are a few dozen petabyte class Teradata relational databases installed, the largest of which exceeds 50 PB.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Systems up until 2008 were 100% structured relational data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Since then, Teradata has added semi structured data types including XML, JSON, and Avro.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] (now LexisNexis Risk Solutions) developed a C++-based distributed platform for data processing and querying known as the HPCC Systems platform.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This system automatically partitions, distributes, stores and delivers structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data across multiple commodity servers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Users can write data processing pipelines and queries in a declarative dataflow programming language called ECL.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Data analysts working in ECL are not required to define data schemas upfront and can rather focus on the particular problem at hand, reshaping data in the best possible manner as they develop the solution.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2004, LexisNexis acquired Seisint Inc. and their high-speed parallel processing platform and successfully used this platform to integrate the data systems of Choicepoint Inc. when they acquired that company in 2008.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2011, the HPCC systems platform was open-sourced under the Apache v2.0 License.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] CERN and other physics experiments have collected big data sets for many decades, usually analyzed via high-throughput computing rather than the map-reduce architectures usually meant by the current "big data" movement.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2004, Google published a paper on a process called MapReduce that uses a similar architecture.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The MapReduce concept provides a parallel processing model, and an associated implementation was released to process huge amounts of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] With MapReduce, queries are split and distributed across parallel nodes and processed in parallel (the "map" step).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The results are then gathered and delivered (the "reduce" step).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The framework was very successful, so others wanted to replicate the algorithm.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Therefore, an implementation of the MapReduce framework was adopted by an Apache open-source project named "Hadoop".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Apache Spark was developed in 2012 in response to limitations in the MapReduce paradigm, as it adds in-memory processing and the ability to set up many operations (not just map followed by reducing).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] MIKE2.0 is an open approach to information management that acknowledges the need for revisions due to big data implications identified in an article titled "Big Data Solution Offering".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The methodology addresses handling big data in terms of useful permutations of data sources, complexity in interrelationships, and difficulty in deleting (or modifying) individual records.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Studies in 2012 showed that a multiple-layer architecture was one option to address the issues that big data presents.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A distributed parallel architecture distributes data across multiple servers; these parallel execution environments can dramatically improve data processing speeds.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This type of architecture inserts data into a parallel DBMS, which implements the use of MapReduce and Hadoop frameworks.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This type of framework looks to make the processing power transparent to the end-user by using a front-end application server.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The data lake allows an organization to shift its focus from centralized control to a shared model to respond to the changing dynamics of information management.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This enables quick segregation of data into the data lake, thereby reducing the overhead time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Multidimensional big data can also be represented as OLAP data cubes or, mathematically, tensors.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Array database systems have set out to provide storage and high-level query support on this data type.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Although, many approaches and technologies have been developed, it still remains difficult to carry out machine learning with big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Some MPP relational databases have the ability to store and manage petabytes of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Implicit is the ability to load, monitor, back up, and optimize the use of the large data tables in the RDBMS.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] DARPA's Topological Data Analysis program seeks the fundamental structure of massive data sets and in 2008 the technology went public with the launch of a company called "Ayasdi".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The practitioners of big data analytics processes are generally hostile to slower shared storage, preferring direct-attached storage (DAS) in its various forms from solid state drive (SSD) to high capacity SATA disk buried inside parallel processing nodes.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The perception of shared storage architectures—storage area network (SAN) and network-attached storage (NAS)— is that they are relatively slow, complex, and expensive.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] These qualities are not consistent with big data analytics systems that thrive on system performance, commodity infrastructure, and low cost.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Real or near-real-time information delivery is one of the defining characteristics of big data analytics.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Latency is therefore avoided whenever and wherever possible.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Data in direct-attached memory or disk is good—data on memory or disk at the other end of an FC SAN connection is not.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The cost of an SAN at the scale needed for analytics applications is much higher than other storage techniques.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data has increased the demand of information management specialists so much so that Software AG, Oracle Corporation, IBM, Microsoft, SAP, EMC, HP, and Dell have spent more than $15 billion on software firms specializing in data management and analytics.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2010, this industry was worth more than $100 billion and was growing at almost 10 percent a year, about twice as fast as the software business as a whole.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Developed economies increasingly use data-intensive technologies.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] There are 4.6 billion mobile-phone subscriptions worldwide, and between 1 billion and 2 billion people accessing the internet.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Between 1990 and 2005, more than 1 billion people worldwide entered the middle class, which means more people became more literate, which in turn led to information growth.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The world's effective capacity to exchange information through telecommunication networks was 281 petabytes in 1986, 471 petabytes in 1993, 2.2 exabytes in 2000, 65 exabytes in 2007 and predictions put the amount of internet traffic at 667 exabytes annually by 2014.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] According to one estimate, one-third of the globally stored information is in the form of alphanumeric text and still image data, which is the format most useful for most big data applications.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This also shows the potential of yet unused data (i.e. in the form of video and audio content).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] While many vendors offer off-the-shelf products for big data, experts promote the development of in-house custom-tailored systems if the company has sufficient technical capabilities.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The use and adoption of big data within governmental processes allows efficiencies in terms of cost, productivity, and innovation, but comes with flaws.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Data analysis often requires multiple parts of government (central and local) to work in collaboration and create new and innovative processes to deliver the desired outcome.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A common government organization that makes use of big data is the National Security Agency (NSA), which monitors the activities of the Internet constantly in search for potential patterns of suspicious or illegal activities their system may pick up.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Civil registration and vital statistics (CRVS) collects all certificates status from birth to death.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] CRVS is a source of big data for governments.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Research on the effective usage of information and communication technologies for development (also known as "ICT4D") suggests that big data technology can make important contributions but also present unique challenges to international development.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Advancements in big data analysis offer cost-effective opportunities to improve decision-making in critical development areas such as health care, employment, economic productivity, crime, security, and natural disaster and resource management.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Additionally, user-generated data offers new opportunities to give the unheard a voice.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] However, longstanding challenges for developing regions such as inadequate technological infrastructure and economic and human resource scarcity exacerbate existing concerns with big data such as privacy, imperfect methodology, and interoperability issues.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The challenge of "big data for development" is currently evolving toward the application of this data through machine learning, known as "artificial intelligence for development (AI4D).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A major practical application of big data for development has been "fighting poverty with data".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2015, Blumenstock and colleagues estimated predicted poverty and wealth from mobile phone metadata and in 2016 Jean and colleagues combined satellite imagery and machine learning to predict poverty.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] At the same time, working with digital trace data instead of traditional survey data does not eliminate the traditional challenges involved in the field of international quantitative analysis.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Priorities may change, but the fundamental discussions remain the same.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big Data is being rapidly adopted in Finance to 1) speed up processing and 2) deliver better, more informed inferences, both internally and to the clients of the financial institutions.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big Data has also been a typical concept within the field of alternative financial service.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Some of the major areas involve crowd-funding platforms and crypto currency exchanges.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Some areas of improvement are more aspirational than actually implemented.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The level of data generated within healthcare systems is not trivial.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] With the added adoption of mHealth, eHealth and wearable technologies the volume of data will continue to increase.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This includes electronic health record data, imaging data, patient generated data, sensor data, and other forms of difficult to process data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] There is now an even greater need for such environments to pay greater attention to data and information quality.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] While extensive information in healthcare is now electronic, it fits under the big data umbrella as most is unstructured and difficult to use.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The use of big data in healthcare has raised significant ethical challenges ranging from risks for individual rights, privacy and autonomy, to transparency and trust.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data in health research is particularly promising in terms of exploratory biomedical research, as data-driven analysis can move forward more quickly than hypothesis-driven research.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Then, trends seen in data analysis can be tested in traditional, hypothesis-driven follow up biological research and eventually clinical research.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A related application sub-area, that heavily relies on big data, within the healthcare field is that of computer-aided diagnosis in medicine.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] For instance, for epilepsy monitoring it is customary to create 5 to 10 GB of data daily.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Similarly, a single uncompressed image of breast tomosynthesis averages 450 MB of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] These are just a few of the many examples where computer-aided diagnosis uses big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] For this reason, big data has been recognized as one of the seven key challenges that computer-aided diagnosis systems need to overcome in order to reach the next level of performance.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A McKinsey Global Institute study found a shortage of 1.5 million highly trained data professionals and managers and a number of universities including University of Tennessee and UC Berkeley, have created masters programs to meet this demand.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Private boot camps have also developed programs to meet that demand, including paid programs like The Data Incubator or General Assembly.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In the specific field of marketing, one of the problems stressed by Wedel and Kannan is that marketing has several sub domains (e.g., advertising, promotions, product development, branding) that all use different types of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] To understand how the media uses big data, it is first necessary to provide some context into the mechanism used for media process.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] It has been suggested by Nick Couldry and Joseph Turow that practitioners in media and advertising approach big data as many actionable points of information about millions of individuals.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The industry appears to be moving away from the traditional approach of using specific media environments such as newspapers, magazines, or television shows and instead taps into consumers with technologies that reach targeted people at optimal times in optimal locations.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The ultimate aim is to serve or convey, a message or content that is (statistically speaking) in line with the consumer's mindset.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] For example, publishing environments are increasingly tailoring messages (advertisements) and content (articles) to appeal to consumers that have been exclusively gleaned through various data-mining activities.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Channel 4, the British public-service television broadcaster, is a leader in the field of big data and data analysis.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Health insurance providers are collecting data on social "determinants of health" such as food and TV consumption, marital status, clothing size, and purchasing habits, from which they make predictions on health costs, in order to spot health issues in their clients.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] It is controversial whether these predictions are currently being used for pricing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data and the IoT work in conjunction.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Data extracted from IoT devices provides a mapping of device inter-connectivity.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Such mappings have been used by the media industry, companies, and governments to more accurately target their audience and increase media efficiency.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The IoT is also increasingly adopted as a means of gathering sensory data, and this sensory data has been used in medical, manufacturing and transportation contexts.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Especially since 2015, big data has come to prominence within business operations as a tool to help employees work more efficiently and streamline the collection and distribution of information technology (IT).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The use of big data to resolve IT and data collection issues within an enterprise is called IT operations analytics (ITOA).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] By applying big data principles into the concepts of machine intelligence and deep computing, IT departments can predict potential issues and prevent them.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] ITOA businesses offer platforms for systems management that bring data silos together and generate insights from the whole of the system rather than from isolated pockets of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Compared to survey-based data collection, big data has low cost per data point, applies analysis techniques via machine learning and data mining, and includes diverse and new data sources, e.g., registers, social media, apps, and other forms digital data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Since 2018, survey scientists have started to examine how big data and survey science can complement each other to allow researchers and practitioners to improve the production of statistics and its quality.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In 2021, the founding members of BigSurv received the Warren J.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Mitofsky Innovators Award from the American Association for Public Opinion Research.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data is notable in marketing due to the constant "datafication" of everyday consumers of the internet, in which all forms of data are tracked.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The datafication of consumers can be defined as quantifying many of or all human behaviors for the purpose of marketing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The increasingly digital world of rapid datafication makes this idea relevant to marketing because the amount of data constantly grows exponentially.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] It is predicted to increase from 44 to 163 zettabytes within the span of five years.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The size of big data can often be difficult to navigate for marketers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] As a result, adopters of big data may find themselves at a disadvantage.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Algorithmic findings can be difficult to achieve with such large datasets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data in marketing is a highly lucrative tool that can be used for large corporations, its value being as a result of the possibility of predicting significant trends, interests, or statistical outcomes in a consumer-based manner.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Real-time market responsiveness is important for marketers because of the ability to shift marketing efforts and correct to current trends, which is helpful in maintaining relevance to consumers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] This can supply corporations with the information necessary to predict the wants and needs of consumers in advance.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Data-driven market ambidexterity are being highly fueled by big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] New models and algorithms are being developed to make significant predictions about certain economic and social situations.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data can be used to improve training and understanding competitors, using sport sensors.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] It is also possible to predict winners in a match using big data analytics.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Future performance of players could be predicted as well.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Thus, players' value and salary is determined by data collected throughout the season.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In Formula One races, race cars with hundreds of sensors generate terabytes of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] These sensors collect data points from tire pressure to fuel burn efficiency.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Based on the data, engineers and data analysts decide whether adjustments should be made in order to win a race.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Besides, using big data, race teams try to predict the time they will finish the race beforehand, based on simulations using data collected over the season.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] During the COVID-19 pandemic, big data was raised as a way to minimise the impact of the disease.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Significant applications of big data included minimizing the spread of the virus, case identification and development of medical treatment.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Governments used big data to track infected people to minimise spread.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Early adopters included China, Taiwan, South Korea, and Israel.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Encrypted search and cluster formation in big data were demonstrated in March 2014 at the American Society of Engineering Education.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Gautam Siwach engaged at *Tackling the challenges of Big Data* by MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory and Amir Esmailpour at the UNH Research Group investigated the key features of big data as the formation of clusters and their interconnections.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] They focused on the security of big data and the orientation of the term towards the presence of different types of data in an encrypted form at cloud interface by providing the raw definitions and real-time examples within the technology.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Moreover, they proposed an approach for identifying the encoding technique to advance towards an expedited search over encrypted text leading to the security enhancements in big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In March 2012, The White House announced a national "Big Data Initiative" that consisted of six federal departments and agencies committing more than $200 million to big data research projects.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The initiative included a National Science Foundation "Expeditions in Computing" grant of $10 million over five years to the AMPLab at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The AMPLab also received funds from DARPA, and over a dozen industrial sponsors and uses big data to attack a wide range of problems from predicting traffic congestion to fighting cancer.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The White House Big Data Initiative also included a commitment by the Department of Energy to provide $25 million in funding over five years to establish the Scalable Data Management, Analysis and Visualization (SDAV) Institute, led by the Energy Department's Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The SDAV Institute aims to bring together the expertise of six national laboratories and seven universities to develop new tools to help scientists manage and visualize data on the department's supercomputers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The U.S. state of Massachusetts announced the Massachusetts Big Data Initiative in May 2012, which provides funding from the state government and private companies to a variety of research institutions.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology hosts the Intel Science and Technology Center for Big Data in the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, combining government, corporate, and institutional funding and research efforts.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The European Commission is funding the two-year-long Big Data Public Private Forum through their Seventh Framework Program to engage companies, academics and other stakeholders in discussing big data issues.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The project aims to define a strategy in terms of research and innovation to guide supporting actions from the European Commission in the successful implementation of the big data economy.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Outcomes of this project will be used as input for Horizon 2020, their next framework program.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The British government announced in March 2014 the founding of the Alan Turing Institute, named after the computer pioneer and code-breaker, which will focus on new ways to collect and analyze large data sets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] At the University of Waterloo Stratford Campus Canadian Open Data Experience (CODE) Inspiration Day, participants demonstrated how using data visualization can increase the understanding and appeal of big data sets and communicate their story to the world.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Computational social sciences – Anyone can use application programming interfaces (APIs) provided by big data holders, such as Google and Twitter, to do research in the social and behavioral sciences.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis et al. used Google Trends data to demonstrate that Internet users from countries with a higher per capita gross domestic products (GDPs) are more likely to search for information about the future than information about the past.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The findings suggest there may be a link between online behaviors and real-world economic indicators.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The authors of the study examined Google queries logs made by ratio of the volume of searches for the coming year (2011) to the volume of searches for the previous year (2009), which they call the "future orientation index".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] They compared the future orientation index to the per capita GDP of each country, and found a strong tendency for countries where Google users inquire more about the future to have a higher GDP.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Tobias Preis and his colleagues Helen Susannah Moat and H.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Eugene Stanley introduced a method to identify online precursors for stock market moves, using trading strategies based on search volume data provided by Google Trends.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Their analysis of Google search volume for 98 terms of varying financial relevance, published in *Scientific Reports*, suggests that increases in search volume for financially relevant search terms tend to precede large losses in financial markets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data sets come with algorithmic challenges that previously did not exist.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Hence, there is seen by some to be a need to fundamentally change the processing ways.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] A research question that is asked about big data sets is whether it is necessary to look at the full data to draw certain conclusions about the properties of the data or if is a sample is good enough.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] The name big data itself contains a term related to size and this is an important characteristic of big data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] But sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] To predict downtime it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] Big data can be broken down by various data point categories such as demographic, psychographic, behavioral, and transactional data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p01] With large sets of data points, marketers are able to create and use more customized segments of consumers for more strategic targeting.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Critiques of the big data paradigm come in two flavors: those that question the implications of the approach itself, and those that question the way it is currently done.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] One approach to this criticism is the field of critical data studies.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Mark Graham has leveled broad critiques at Chris Anderson's assertion that big data will spell the end of theory: focusing in particular on the notion that big data must always be contextualized in their social, economic, and political contexts.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Even as companies invest eight- and nine-figure sums to derive insight from information streaming in from suppliers and customers, less than 40% of employees have sufficiently mature processes and skills to do so.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] To overcome this insight deficit, big data, no matter how comprehensive or well analyzed, must be complemented by "big judgment", according to an article in the *Harvard Business Review*.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Much in the same line, it has been pointed out that the decisions based on the analysis of big data are inevitably "informed by the world as it was in the past, or, at best, as it currently is".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Fed by a large number of data on past experiences, algorithms can predict future development if the future is similar to the past.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] If the system's dynamics of the future change (if it is not a stationary process), the past can say little about the future.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In order to make predictions in changing environments, it would be necessary to have a thorough understanding of the systems dynamic, which requires theory.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] As a response to this critique Alemany Oliver and Vayre suggest to use "abductive reasoning as a first step in the research process in order to bring context to consumers' digital traces and make new theories emerge".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Additionally, it has been suggested to combine big data approaches with computer simulations, such as agent-based models and complex systems.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Agent-based models are increasingly getting better in predicting the outcome of social complexities of even unknown future scenarios through computer simulations that are based on a collection of mutually interdependent algorithms.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Finally, the use of multivariate methods that probe for the latent structure of the data, such as factor analysis and cluster analysis, have proven useful as analytic approaches that go well beyond the bi-variate approaches (e.g. contingency tables) typically employed with smaller data sets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In health and biology, conventional scientific approaches are based on experimentation.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] For these approaches, the limiting factor is the relevant data that can confirm or refute the initial hypothesis.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] A new postulate is accepted now in biosciences: the information provided by the data in huge volumes (omics) without prior hypothesis is complementary and sometimes necessary to conventional approaches based on experimentation.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In the massive approaches it is the formulation of a relevant hypothesis to explain the data that is the limiting factor.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] The search logic is reversed and the limits of induction ("Glory of Science and Philosophy scandal", C.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Privacy advocates are concerned about the threat to privacy represented by increasing storage and integration of personally identifiable information; expert panels have released various policy recommendations to conform practice to expectations of privacy.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] The misuse of big data in several cases by media, companies, and even the government has allowed for abolition of trust in almost every fundamental institution holding up society.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Barocas and Nissenbaum argue that one way of protecting individual users is by being informed about the types of information being collected, with whom it is shared, under what constraints and for what purposes.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] The "V" model of big data is concerning as it centers around computational scalability and lacks in a loss around the perceptibility and understandability of information.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Large data sets have been analyzed by computing machines for well over a century, including the US census analytics performed by IBM's punch-card machines which computed statistics including means and variances of populations across the whole continent.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In more recent decades, science experiments such as CERN have produced data on similar scales to current commercial "big data".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Ulf-Dietrich Reips and Uwe Matzat wrote in 2014 that big data had become a "fad" in scientific research.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Researcher danah boyd has raised concerns about the use of big data in science neglecting principles such as choosing a representative sample by being too concerned about handling the huge amounts of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] This approach may lead to results that have a bias in one way or another.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Integration across heterogeneous data resources—some that might be considered big data and others not—presents formidable logistical as well as analytical challenges, but many researchers argue that such integrations are likely to represent the most promising new frontiers in science.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In the provocative article "Critical Questions for Big Data", the authors title big data a part of mythology: "large data sets offer a higher form of intelligence and knowledge [...], with the aura of truth, objectivity, and accuracy".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Users of big data are often "lost in the sheer volume of numbers", and "working with Big Data is still subjective, and what it quantifies does not necessarily have a closer claim on objective truth".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Recent developments in BI domain, such as pro-active reporting especially target improvements in the usability of big data, through automated filtering of non-useful data and correlations.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Big data analysis is often shallow compared to analysis of smaller data sets.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In many big data projects, there is no large data analysis happening, but the challenge is the extract, transform, load part of data pre-processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Big data is a buzzword and a "vague term", but at the same time an "obsession" with entrepreneurs, consultants, scientists, and the media.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Big data showcases such as Google Flu Trends failed to deliver good predictions in recent years, overstating the flu outbreaks by a factor of two.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Similarly, Academy Awards and election predictions solely based on Twitter were more often off than on target.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Big data often poses the same challenges as small data; adding more data does not solve problems of bias, but may emphasize other problems.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In particular data sources such as Twitter are not representative of the overall population, and results drawn from such sources may then lead to wrong conclusions.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Google Translate—which is based on big data statistical analysis of text—does a good job at translating web pages.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] However, results from specialized domains may be dramatically skewed.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] On the other hand, big data may also introduce new problems, such as the multiple comparisons problem: simultaneously testing a large set of hypotheses is likely to produce many false results that mistakenly appear significant.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Furthermore, big data analytics results are only as good as the model on which they are predicated.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] In an example, big data took part in attempting to predict the results of the 2016 U.S. presidential election with varying degrees of success.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Big data has been used in policing and surveillance by institutions like law enforcement and corporations ().
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Due to the less visible nature of data-based surveillance as compared to traditional methods of policing, objections to big data policing are less likely to arise.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] If these potential problems are not corrected or regulated, the effects of big data policing may continue to shape societal hierarchies.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/big-data-p02] Brayne also notes that the conscientious use of big data policing could prevent individual-level biases from becoming institutional biases.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The United States Census Bureau history illustrates the evolution of data processing from manual through electronic procedures.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Although widespread use of the term *data processing* dates only from the 1950s, data processing functions have been performed manually for millennia.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] For example, bookkeeping involves functions such as posting transactions and producing reports like the balance sheet and the cash flow statement.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Completely manual methods were augmented by the application of mechanical or electronic calculators.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The 1890 United States census schedule was the first to gather data by individual rather than household.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] A number of questions could be answered by making a check in the appropriate box on the form.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] From 1850 to 1880 the Census Bureau employed "a system of tallying, which, by reason of the increasing number of combinations of classifications required, became increasingly complex.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Only a limited number of combinations could be recorded in one tally, so it was necessary to handle the schedules 5 or 6 times, for as many independent tallies." "It took over 7 years to publish the results of the 1880 census" using manual processing methods.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The term *automatic data processing* was applied to operations performed by means of unit record equipment, such as Herman Hollerith's application of punched card equipment for the 1890 United States census.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] "Using Hollerith's punchcard equipment, the Census Office was able to complete tabulating most of the 1890 census data in 2 to 3 years, compared with 7 to 8 years for the 1880 census.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] It is estimated that using Hollerith's system saved some $5 million in processing costs" in 1890 dollars even though there were twice as many questions as in 1880.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Computerized data processing, or electronic data processing represents a later development, with a computer used instead of several independent pieces of equipment.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The Census Bureau first made limited use of electronic computers for the 1950 United States census, using a UNIVAC I system, delivered in 1952.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The term *data processing* has mostly been subsumed by the more general term *information technology* (IT).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The older term "data processing" is suggestive of older technologies.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] For example, in 1996 the *Data Processing Management Association* (DPMA) changed its name to the *Association of Information Technology Professionals*.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Nevertheless, the terms are approximately synonymous.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Commercial data processing involves a large volume of input data, relatively few computational operations, and a large volume of output.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] For example, an insurance company needs to keep records on tens or hundreds of thousands of policies, print and mail bills, and receive and post payments.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] In science and engineering, the terms *data processing* and *information systems* are considered too broad, and the term *data processing* is typically used for the initial stage followed by a data analysis in the second stage of the overall data handling.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Data analysis uses specialized algorithms and statistical calculations that are less often observed in a typical general business environment.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] For data analysis, software suites like SPSS or SAS, or their free counterparts such as DAP, gretl, or PSPP are often used.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] These tools are usually helpful for processing various huge data sets, as they are able to handle enormous amount of statistical analysis.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] A **data processing system** is a combination of machines, people, and processes that for a set of inputs produces a defined set of outputs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The inputs and outputs are interpreted as data, facts, information etc. depending on the interpreter's relation to the system.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] A term commonly used synonymously with *data or storage (codes) processing system* is *information system*.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] With regard particularly to electronic data processing, the corresponding concept is referred to as **electronic data processing system**.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] A very simple example of a data processing system is the process of maintaining a check register.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Transactions— checks and deposits— are recorded as they occur and the transactions are summarized to determine a current balance.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] Monthly the data recorded in the register is reconciled with a hopefully identical list of transactions processed by the bank.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] A more sophisticated record keeping system might further identify the transactions— for example deposits by source or checks by type, such as charitable contributions.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] This information might be used to obtain information like the total of all contributions for the year.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/data-processing] The important thing about this example is that it is a *system*, in which, all transactions are recorded consistently, and the same method of bank reconciliation is used each time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Lambda architecture depends on a data model with an append-only, immutable data source that serves as a system of record.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] It is intended for ingesting and processing timestamped events that are appended to existing events rather than overwriting them.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] State is determined from the natural time-based ordering of the data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Lambda architecture describes a system consisting of three layers: batch processing, speed (or real-time) processing, and a serving layer for responding to queries.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The processing layers ingest from an immutable master copy of the entire data set.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] This paradigm was first described by Nathan Marz in a blog post titled "How to beat the CAP theorem" in which he originally termed it the "batch/realtime architecture".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The batch layer precomputes results using a distributed processing system that can handle very large quantities of data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The batch layer aims at perfect accuracy by being able to process *all* available data when generating views.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] This means it can fix any errors by recomputing based on the complete data set, then updating existing views.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Output is typically stored in a read-only database, with updates completely replacing existing precomputed views.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] By 2014, Apache Hadoop was estimated to be a leading batch-processing system.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Later, other, relational databases like Snowflake, Redshift, Synapse and Big Query were also used in this role.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The speed layer processes data streams in real time and without the requirements of fix-ups or completeness.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] This layer sacrifices throughput as it aims to minimize latency by providing real-time views into the most recent data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Essentially, the speed layer is responsible for filling the "gap" caused by the batch layer's lag in providing views based on the most recent data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] This layer's views may not be as accurate or complete as the ones eventually produced by the batch layer, but they are available almost immediately after data is received, and can be replaced when the batch layer's views for the same data become available.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Stream-processing technologies typically used in this layer include Apache Kafka, Amazon Kinesis, Apache Storm, SQLstream, Apache Samza, Apache Spark, Azure Stream Analytics, Apache Flink.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Output is typically stored on fast NoSQL databases., or as a commit log.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Output from the batch and speed layers are stored in the serving layer, which responds to ad-hoc queries by returning precomputed views or building views from the processed data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Examples of technologies used in the serving layer include Apache Druid, Apache Pinot, ClickHouse and Tinybird which provide a single platform to handle output from both layers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Dedicated stores used in the serving layer include Apache Cassandra, Apache HBase, Azure Cosmos DB, MongoDB, VoltDB or Elasticsearch for speed-layer output, and Elephant DB, Apache Impala, SAP HANA or Apache Hive for batch-layer output.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] To optimize the data set and improve query efficiency, various rollup and aggregation techniques are executed on raw data, while estimation techniques are employed to further reduce computation costs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] And while expensive full recomputation is required for fault tolerance, incremental computation algorithms may be selectively added to increase efficiency, and techniques such as *partial computation* and resource-usage optimizations can effectively help lower latency.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Metamarkets, which provides analytics for companies in the programmatic advertising space, employs a version of the lambda architecture that uses Druid for storing and serving both the streamed and batch-processed data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] For running analytics on its advertising data warehouse, Yahoo has taken a similar approach, also using Apache Storm, Apache Hadoop, and Druid.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The Netflix Suro project has separate processing paths for data, but does not strictly follow lambda architecture since the paths may be intended to serve different purposes and not necessarily to provide the same type of views.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Nevertheless, the overall idea is to make selected real-time event data available to queries with very low latency, while the entire data set is also processed via a batch pipeline.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The latter is intended for applications that are less sensitive to latency and require a map-reduce type of processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Criticism of lambda architecture has focused on its inherent complexity and its limiting influence.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] The batch and streaming sides each require a different code base that must be maintained and kept in sync so that processed data produces the same result from both paths.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Yet attempting to abstract the code bases into a single framework puts many of the specialized tools in the batch and real-time ecosystems out of reach.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Jay Kreps introduced the kappa architecture to use a pure streaming approach with a single code base.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] In a technical discussion over the merits of employing a pure streaming approach, it was noted that using a flexible streaming framework such as Apache Samza could provide some of the same benefits as batch processing without the latency.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/lambda-architecture] Such a streaming framework could allow for collecting and processing arbitrarily large windows of data, accommodate blocking, and handle state.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This is the sequential paradigm that is most familiar.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Variations do exist (such as inner loops, structures and such), but they ultimately boil down to that construct.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] It assumes the instruction `vector_sum` works.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Although this is what happens with instruction intrinsics, much information is actually not taken into account here such as the number of vector components and their data format.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] You can see however, this method reduces the number of decoded instructions from *numElements * componentsPerElement* to *numElements*.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The number of jump instructions is also decreased, as the loop is run fewer times.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] These gains result from the parallel execution of the four mathematical operations.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] What happened however is that the packed SIMD register holds a certain amount of data so it's not possible to get more parallelism.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The speed up is somewhat limited by the assumption we made of performing four parallel operations (please note this is common for both AltiVec and SSE).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] In this paradigm, the whole dataset is defined, rather than each component block being defined separately.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Describing the set of data is assumed to be in the first two rows.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] After that, the result is inferred from the sources and kernel.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] For simplicity, there's a 1:1 mapping between input and output data but this does not need to be.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Applied kernels can also be much more complex.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] An implementation of this paradigm can "unroll" a loop internally.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This allows throughput to scale with chip complexity, easily utilizing hundreds of ALUs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The elimination of complex data patterns makes much of this extra power available.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] While stream processing is a branch of SIMD/MIMD processing, they must not be confused.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Although SIMD implementations can often work in a "streaming" manner, their performance is not comparable: the model envisions a very different usage pattern which allows far greater performance by itself.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] It has been noted that when applied on generic processors such as standard CPU, only a 1.5x speedup can be reached.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] By contrast, ad-hoc stream processors easily reach over 10x performance, mainly attributed to the more efficient memory access and higher levels of parallel processing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Although there are various degrees of flexibility allowed by the model, stream processors usually impose some limitations on the kernel or stream size.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] For example, consumer hardware often lacks the ability to perform high-precision math, lacks complex indirection chains or presents lower limits on the number of instructions which can be executed.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Stanford University stream processing projects included the Stanford Real-Time Programmable Shading Project started in 1999.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] A prototype called Imagine was developed in 2002.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] A project called Merrimac ran until about 2004.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] AT&T also researched stream-enhanced processors as graphics processing units rapidly evolved in both speed and functionality.[1] Since these early days, dozens of stream processing languages have been developed, as well as specialized hardware.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The most immediate challenge in the realm of parallel processing does not lie as much in the type of hardware architecture used, but in how easy it will be to program the system in question in a real-world environment with acceptable performance.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Machines like Imagine use a straightforward single-threaded model with automated dependencies, memory allocation and DMA scheduling.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This in itself is a result of the research at MIT and Stanford in finding an optimal *layering of tasks* between programmer, tools and hardware.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Programmers beat tools in mapping algorithms to parallel hardware, and tools beat programmers in figuring out smartest memory allocation schemes, etc.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Of particular concern are MIMD designs such as Cell, for which the programmer needs to deal with application partitioning across multiple cores and deal with process synchronization and load balancing.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] A drawback of SIMD programming was the issue of array-of-structures (AoS) and structure-of-arrays (SoA).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] When multiple of these structures exist in memory they are placed end to end creating an arrays in an *array of structures* (AoS) topology.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This means that should some algorithm be applied to the location of each particle in turn it must skip over memory locations containing the other attributes.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] If these attributes are not needed this results in wasteful usage of the CPU cache.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Additionally, a SIMD instruction will typically expect the data it will operate on to be contiguous in memory, the elements may also need to be aligned.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] By moving the memory location of the data out of the structure data can be better organised for efficient access in a stream and for SIMD instructions to operate one.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] A *structure of arrays* (SoA), as shown below, can allow this.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Instead of holding the data in the structure, it holds only pointers (memory locations) for the data.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Shortcomings are that if multiple attributes to of an object are to be operated on they might now be distant in memory and so result in a cache miss.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The aligning and any needed padding lead to increased memory usage.
