[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Because of the SIMD nature of the stream processor's execution units (ALUs clusters), read/write operations are expected to happen in bulk, so memories are optimized for high bandwidth rather than low latency (this is a difference from Rambus and DDR SDRAM, for example).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This also allows for efficient memory bus negotiations.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Most (90%) of a stream processor's work is done on-chip, requiring only 1% of the global data to be stored to memory.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This is where knowing the kernel temporaries and dependencies pays.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Internally, a stream processor features some clever communication and management circuits but what's interesting is the *Stream Register File* (SRF).
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This is conceptually a large cache in which stream data is stored to be transferred to external memory in bulks.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] As a cache-like software-controlled structure to the various ALUs, the SRF is shared between all the various ALU clusters.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The key concept and innovation here done with Stanford's Imagine chip is that the compiler is able to automate and allocate memory in an optimal way, fully transparent to the programmer.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] The dependencies between kernel functions and data is known through the programming model which enables the compiler to perform flow analysis and optimally pack the SRFs.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Commonly, this cache and DMA management can take up the majority of a project's schedule, something the stream processor (or at least Imagine) totally automates.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Tests done at Stanford showed that the compiler did an as well or better job at scheduling memory than if you hand tuned the thing with much effort.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] There is proof; there can be a lot of clusters because inter-cluster communication is assumed to be rare.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] Internally however, each cluster can efficiently exploit a much lower amount of ALUs because intra-cluster communication is common and thus needs to be highly efficient.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] To keep those ALUs fetched with data, each ALU is equipped with local register files (LRFs), which are basically its usable registers.
[src:batch-vs-streaming/stream-processing] This three-tiered data access pattern, makes it easy to keep temporary data away from slow memories, thus making the silicon implementation highly efficient and power-saving.
